{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619304"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:30:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:30:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16550"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16550"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.3,0.43,0,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75719"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9241"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61237"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"11340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21898"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75719"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman with Parkinson\u0027s disease has been taking levodopa-carbidopa for five years. She now experiences increasing periods where her medication seems less effective, with worsening tremor and rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would be most appropriate to add as adjunct therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dopamine receptor antagonists","Dopamine reuptake inhibitors","Catechol-O-methyltransferase inhibitors","Gamma-aminobutyric acid agonists","Glutamate receptor antagonists"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatechol-O-methyltransferase (COMT) inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E are effective adjunct therapy for Parkinson\u0027s disease. They work by preventing the peripheral breakdown of levodopa, thereby increasing its bioavailability and effectiveness. Examples include entacapone and tolcapone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine receptor antagonists\u003C/strong\u003E would worsen Parkinson\u0027s disease by blocking dopamine signalling\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine reuptake inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically used in Parkinson\u0027s disease treatment\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma-aminobutyric acid agonists\u003C/strong\u003E do not directly affect dopamine levels or function\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlutamate receptor antagonists\u003C/strong\u003E are not standard therapy for Parkinson\u0027s disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECOMT inhibitors are particularly useful in managing motor fluctuations that occur with long-term levodopa therapy. They are often combined with levodopa/carbidopa preparations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Catechol-O-methyltransferase (COMT) inhibitors prevent the peripheral breakdown of levodopa, increasing its bioavailability.","COMT inhibitors are used as adjunct therapy when Parkinson\u0027s disease symptoms are not adequately controlled with levodopa alone.","Other adjunct medications for Parkinson\u0027s disease include monoamine oxidase B inhibitors and dopamine agonists."],"references":["Kobylecki C. Update on the diagnosis and management of Parkinson\u0027s disease. Clin Med (Lond). 2020 Jul;20(4):393-398. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2020-0220. PMID: 32675145; PMCID: PMC7385761.","Regensburger M, Ip CW, Kohl Z, Schrader C, Urban PP, Kassubek J, Jost WH. Clinical benefit of MAO-B and COMT inhibition in Parkinson\u0027s disease: practical considerations. J Neural Transm (Vienna). 2023 Jun;130(6):847-861. doi: 10.1007/s00702-023-02623-8. Epub 2023 Mar 24. PMID: 36964457; PMCID: PMC10199833.","DeMaagd G, Philip A. Parkinson\u0027s Disease and Its Management: Part 1: Disease Entity, Risk Factors, Pathophysiology, Clinical Presentation, and Diagnosis. P T. 2015 Aug;40(8):504-32. PMID: 26236139; PMCID: PMC4517533.","Deane KH, Spieker S, Clarke CE. Catechol-O-methyltransferase inhibitors for levodopa-induced complications in Parkinson\u0027s disease. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2004 Oct 18;2004(4):CD004554. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD004554.pub2. PMID: 15495119; PMCID: PMC8830033."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61237"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16550"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61237"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T20:23:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T20:25:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9241"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75719"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.e